7991, 'For everything is history: What was said yesterday is history, what was said a minute ago is history. But, above all, one is led to misjudge the present, because only the study of historical development permits the weighing and evalua­ tion of the interrelationships among the components of the present- day society.', 12950, 0), (57992, 'In such a view, time is not emergent. It is, in fact, the only aspect of reality that cannot emerge from a more fundamental background. We register its reality, always and everywhere, by recognizing the differential character of change: some things change relative to other things. However, the kinds of things that there are also change, and so do the ways in which they change. That is what time is: the transformation of transformation.', 7606, 0), (57993, 'Nurture a desire to be free from the clock.', 5117, 0), (57994, 'We should kill our pasts with each passing day. Blot them out, so that they will not hurt. Each present day could thus be endured more easily, it would not be measured against what no longer exists. As things are, spectres mix with our lives so that there is neither pure memory nor pure life. They clash and try to strangle each other, continually', 3724, 0), (57995, 'there are between life partners sliding layers of history, tectonic plates of it shifting over the decades together.', 12951, 0), (57996, 'Time reveals character.', 4680, 0), (57997, 'Time is information we don''t have. Time is our ignorance.', 11034, 0), (57998, 'Time could heal, but it wouldn''t make wrongs go away. Time came back like a reminder. Time folded with memory. In a moment, everything could fold itself up, and time stand still.', 8917, 0), (57999, 'But when they changed their plans time and time again, the dates became confused, the periods were mislaid, and one day seemed so much like another that one could not feel them pass.', 183, 0), (58000, 'There will be a time, when you ask for nothing but life.', 2878, 0);
